           P.G. Young, LANL                                       1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
 Los Alamos LA150 Library, produced with FKK/GNASH/GSCAN code     1425 1451
   in cooperation with ECN Petten.                                1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       1425 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               1425 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       1425 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     1425 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  1425 1451
VI.5 (Release 5) evaluation by D. Hetrick, N. Larson, D. Larson,  1425 1451
L. Leal, and S. Epperson.                                         1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 5 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        1425 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             1425 1451
significant reactions.  The present evauation utilizes a more     1425 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   1425 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  1425 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    1425 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    1425 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        1425 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      1425 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   1425 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     1425 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                1425 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   1425 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           1425 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         1425 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      1425 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         1425 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      1425 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    1425 1451
Si28 and p + Si28 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  1425 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               1425 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    1425 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       1425 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     1425 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    1425 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    1425 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  1425 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       1425 1451
[Ka88].                                                           1425 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  1425 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    1425 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  1425 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     1425 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   1425 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  1425 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  1425 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      1425 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  1425 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     1425 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     1425 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk [Ig75] and pairing and shell    1425 1451
parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and charged-    1425 1451
particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the         1425 1451
optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission   1425 1451
coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].  1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
DETAILS OF THE n + SI28 ANALYSIS                                  1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  The neutron total cross section above 20 MeV was obtained by    1425 1451
evaluating the experimental data, with a particular emphasis on   1425 1451
the high-accuracy Los Alamos measurements by Finlay [Fi93].       1425 1451
  The Madland global medium-energy optical potential [Ma88] was   1425 1451
used for neutrons above 46 MeV, and the Wilmore-Hodgson           1425 1451
potential [Wi64] was used for lower neutron energies.  The        1425 1451
Madland global medium-energy optical potential was used for       1425 1451
protons above 28 MeV, and the Beccheti-Greenlees potential        1425 1451
[Be69] was used for lower proton energies. In both cases the      1425 1451
transition region to the Madland potential was chosen to          1425 1451
approximately give continuity in the reaction cross section.      1425 1451
For deuterons, the Perey [Pe63] global potential was used; for    1425 1451
alpha particles the MacFadden potential [Ma66] was used; and for  1425 1451
tritons the Beccheti-Greenlees potential [Be71] was used.         1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  While the above optical potentials did describe the             1425 1451
experimental proton nonelastic cross section data fairly well,    1425 1451
we modified the theoretical predictions slightly to better agree  1425 1451
with the measurements, and renormalized the transmission          1425 1451
coefficients accordingly. In addition to using Si nonelastic      1425 1451
proton cross section measurements, we also were guided by p+Al    1425 1451
nonelastic data, scaled by A**2/3.                                1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  Coupled-channel optical model calculations were performed to    1425 1451
determine inelastic scattering on 28Si, for the 0+, 2+, and 4+    1425 1451
states, as well as a DWBA calculation of the inelastic            1425 1451
scattering to the 3- vibrational state, all performed with the    1425 1451
ECIS code [Ra72]. Near 20 MeV neutron energy, inelastic           1425 1451
scattering to these states has been measured by Alarcon and       1425 1451
Rapaport [Al83], and Finlay et al., from Ohio University, and     1425 1451
the inelastic cross sections to these collective states is in     1425 1451
good agreement with the ORNL ENDF evaluation for 28Si. To         1425 1451
produce continuity in the calculated inelastic cross sections up  1425 1451
to 150 MeV, we performed a rotational band (0+, 2+, 4+) coupled   1425 1451
channel calculation using the Madland medium energy potential     1425 1451
(with its imaginary potential reduced by 20%, to approximately    1425 1451
account for the coupling). Deformation parameters were chosen to  1425 1451
reproduce the ENDF/B-VI cross sections at 20 MeV, resulting in    1425 1451
values of beta_2=-0.365, beta_4=+0.22, in good agreement with     1425 1451
Rapaport's values of -0.37, 0.17 respectively. A vibrarional      1425 1451
DWBA calculation (using ECIS) was performed for the 3- state      1425 1451
resulting in beta-3=0.235 (Rapaport obtained 0.23).               1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  Only 2 measurements exist for neutron-induced emission spectra  1425 1451
above 20 MeV for 28Si. New data have been published by the        1425 1451
Louvain group at the 1997 Trieste conference for 63 MeV Si(n,xz)  1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
double-differential spectra (z=p,d,a ejectiles). Additionally,    1425 1451
Haight et al. of Los Alamos have preliminary data for Si(n,xp),   1425 1451
for neutrons up to 50 MeV, including emission spectra at four     1425 1451
angles. Our calculations agree reasonably well with these         1425 1451
measurements. While default level density parameters (using the   1425 1451
Ignatyuk model) were utilized, in the case of 28Al the level      1425 1451
density parameter was slightly modified to optimize agreement     1425 1451
with the Abfalterer total level density measurements based on     1425 1451
fluctuation analyses [Ab93].                                      1425 1451
                                                                  1425 1451
  As an independent validation of our GNASH calculations using    1425 1451
the exciton model, we have also performed FKK calculations. This  1425 1451
was done by implementing a multistep reaction theory recently     1425 1451
developed by Koning and Chadwick, which is particularly suited    1425 1451
to the simultaneous calculation of neutron and proton emission.   1425 1451
The FKK theory describes the forward-peaking very well, as do     1425 1451
our exciton model calculations using the phenomenological         1425 1451
Kalbach angular distribution systematics.                         1425 1451
